{{Infobox political party |name = Senior Citizens Party |logo = [[Image:Senior Citizens Party 1.png]] |colorcode = #FFFFFF |leader = Grahame Leon-Smith |chairman = |president = |spokesperson = |foundation = {{Start date|2004|01|22}} |dissolution = 2014 |ideology = [[Senior citizen]] rights |headquarters = |international = |website = https://web.archive.org/web/20071009150333/http://www.seniorcitizensparty.org.uk/ |country = the United Kingdom |merged = {{nowrap|[[UK Independence Party|UKIP]]<ref name=ukip/>}} }}
The '''Senior Citizens Party''' was a [[political party]] in the [[United Kingdom]] from 2004-2014,<ref name=ukip/> which focused on the rights of people over the age of 50, [[senior citizen]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/south-wales-echo-cardiff/mi_7993/is_2005_Dec_5/drive-recruit-senior-citizens-party/ai_n37679106/|title=Drive to recruit for new senior citizens' party|last=Nifield|first=Phillip|date=5 December 2005|work=South Wales Echo|accessdate=16 February 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> They claimed a membership of several thousand.<ref name=SOA2007/>
The party was founded in January 2004<ref name=time>{{Cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-20136701_ITM|title=Now is your time to stand together|date=24 January 2004|work=Western Daily Press|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> by [[Grahame Leon-Smith]], formerly the party leader, and [[Terry Pattinson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/regionalassembly/news/tm_objectid=14798448&method=full&siteid=50081&headline=old-folk-s-party-switches-sides-name_page.html|title=Old folk's party switches sides|date=26 October 2004|work=The Journal|accessdate=16 February 2010|location=Newcastle}}</ref> They claim that they had previously been lifelong [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] voters respectively, Leon-Smith serving as a councillor for 6 years,<ref name=party>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/may/02/otherparties.localelections2006|title=It's my party ...|last=Boggan|first=Steve|date=2 May 2006|work=The Guardian|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> but had become disillusioned by the breaking of the link between [[Pension provision in the United Kingdom|pensions]] and [[Income in the United Kingdom|average earnings]] by the Conservatives and Labour's failure to restore it. They also campaigned against [[council tax]], proposing a [[local income tax]],<ref name=time/> and campaign for free personal care for the elderly, free off-peak travel, and free [[television license]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3726803.stm#seniors|title=European elections: The manifestos|date=1 June 2004|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref>
The party won 42,861 votes in the [[South East England (European Parliament constituency)|South East]] in the [[European Parliament election, 2004 (United Kingdom)|European Parliament election, 2004]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/vote2004/euro_uk/html/front.stm|title=European Election: United Kingdom Result|date=14 June 2004|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> and stood candidates against [[Tony Blair]] and [[Michael Howard]] in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2005|2005 UK general election]]. Leon-Smith received 151 votes (0.3%) in [[Folkestone and Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Folkestone and Hythe]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/10768/grahame-leon-smith|title=Grahame Leon-Smith: Electoral history and profile|work=The Guardian|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> and Pattinson received 97 votes (0.2%) in [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/10769/terry-pattinson|title=Terry Pattinson: Electoral history and profile|work=The Guardian|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> In the run up to the 2005 General Election the Senior Citizens Party had meetings discussing an [[electoral alliance]] with the [[English Democrats]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alliancefordemocracy.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=56&Itemid=60 |title=Alliance for Democracy – 2005 |date=2010 |work=Alliance for Democracy |accessdate=16 February 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304083114/http://www.alliancefordemocracy.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=56&Itemid=60 |archivedate=4 March 2010 |df= }}</ref> In May 2006, Leon-Smith and Pattinson stood for the party in the [[Runnymede Council election, 2006|Runnymede Borough Council election]], receiving 261 votes between them.<ref name=party/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ww2.runnymede.gov.uk/council/services/election/2006/pages/elect.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060601165059/http://ww2.runnymede.gov.uk/council/services/election/2006/pages/elect.asp|dead-url=yes|archive-date=1 June 2006|title=Elections 2006|work=Runnymede Borough Council|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref>
According to their [[Electoral Commission (UK)|Electoral Commission]] registration, the leader, nominating officer and treasurer was Leon-Smith, whilst Pattinston is Campaigns Officer. Their accounts filed for the years 2004 and 2007 indicate that they had "approximately 4,000 members and associate members". The annual membership fee was £12, but associate members do not pay anything. The ratio of full to associate members was not specified.<ref name=SOA2007>{{Cite web|url=http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/49054/Senior-Citizens-Party-Statement-of-Accounts-2007_29315-21788__E__N__S__W__.pdf|title=Senior Citizens Party Statement of Accounts 2007|work=Electoral Commission|accessdate=16 February 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref> {{Cite web |work=The Electoral Commission |title=Senior Citizens Party, The Statement of Accounts for 2004 |url=http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/templates/search/document.cfm/11953 |accessdate=2006-12-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928032426/http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/templates/search/document.cfm/11953 |archivedate=28 September 2006 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> The Senior Citizens Party merged with UKIP in March 2014, as announced by Leon-Smith at the Ukip conference.<ref name=ukip>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Vt_cglf6UY|title=Conference welcomes Grahame Leon-Smith, chairman, Senior Citizens Party |date=March 5, 2014|work=Official UKIP channel|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=April 14, 2017}}</ref>
